Visualizations of the American Food System

Julia Whiting

Taking annual sales to stand in for farm value, an interesting pattern emerges. Most farms in the United States earn less than $5000. The next most are the top earners, taking in over $100,000 in sales. It would appear that farming as a profession with a reasonable income no longer the norm.

Many farms receive payments from the government through subsidies. Most subsidies fund commodity crops, such as corn, wheat, and cotton. Subsidies are concentrated in states that produce these commodities, mostly in the Midwest and Plains states. Because of the relationship between crops and subsidies, the state that receives the most government payments is not the state with the most farms.

Most farms in the US are relatively small. Many food experts will tell you that farm sizes in the US are growing. Yet most farms are still under .25 square miles (180 acres). Texas has approximately double the number of farms than the next state.

There is a positive relationship between number of farms in a state and number of residents with low food access. Low access to food is defined as living more than one mile away from a groccery store in urban areas, and more than 10 miles away from a groccery store in rural areas. Food insecurity is defined as being unable to provide adequate food for one or more household members at some time during the year. While food access is related to number of farms, food insecurity is not related to access to food. There may be food produced in a state, but the ability of residents to buy that food is another matter entirely.

The majority of crop land in the United States is not used to feed people. Hay and silage, both grown for animal feed, account for 43% of all US cropland. Additionally, 48% of corn and 70% of soy is grown to produce animal feed. In total, approximately 65% of cultivated land in the country produces food not fit for human consumption. In contrast, fruits and vegetables take up just 2% of cropland in the country.

Farmers markets remain concentrated on the coasts. States in New England stand out as having especially high proportions of markets that accept SNAP benefits. California and New York have the most farmers markets in the nation, which makes sense given their populations. Michigan and Illinois have large numbers of farmers’ markets and markets that accept SNAP benefits given their populations.

When looking at the ranking of states by number of farms from 1950-2012, several trends are apparent. Texas and Alaska have had the most and least farms, respectively, for the entire 62 year span. Given the size of Texas and geographical location of Alaska, their positions are not surprising. The states that saw the largest falls in rankings are southern: South Carolina, North Carolina, Mississippi, and Alabama. The states with the largest gains are more dispersed: Oklahoma, Florida, Colorado, and California.

Almost every state lost farms between 1950 and 2012. Texas stands out for several reasons. It has more farms than any other state, which is not necessarily surprising given its area. What is unusual, however, is that Texas has gained a large number of farms during a time when other states experienced losses, or extremely moderate gains. California, for example, went from being the 21st state with the most farms to 5th most from 1950-2012. This sounds impressive, but looking at the actual numbe of farms in the state, it becomes apparent that California’s shift in rankings is mostly due to other states losing farms. In 1950, the state had 137,168 farms, while in 2012 it had 77,857.

Data Sources: Haines, Michael, Fishback, Price, and Rhode, Paul. United States Agriculture Data, 1840 - 2012. Ann Arbor, MI: Inter-university Consortium for Political and Social Research [distributor], 2018-08-20. https://doi.org/10.3886/ICPSR35206.v4

Helsinger, Adam. United States Department of Agriculture Food Environment Atlas. 2017. https://data.world/adamhelsinger/food-environment-atlas
